class="post-meta2"><p>Written by Koos Jansen on March 12, 2014 at 4:34 pm</p></div></div> </article><script async src="//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js?e1a502"></script><div
style="height: 90px; width: 728px; border-top:1px solid rgb(180,180,180); margin-top:105px!important;padding-top:30px;padding-bottom:30px"> <ins
class="adsbygoogle"
style="display:inline-block;width:728px;height:90px;margin-left:-5px"
data-ad-client="ca-pub-1133748844114920"
data-ad-slot="9410455093"></ins></div><script>
(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script><div
id="disqus_thread"><div
id="dsq-content"><ul
id="dsq-comments"><li
class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-1934"><div
id="dsq-comment-header-1934" class="dsq-comment-header"> <cite
id="dsq-cite-1934"> <span
id="dsq-author-user-1934">Zhanglan</span> </cite></div><div
id="dsq-comment-body-1934" class="dsq-comment-body"><div
id="dsq-comment-message-1934" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>This article is slightly old, but offers a clear insight into the mechanics of Futures markets (SIMEX no longer exists as the Singapore International Monetary Exchange, and has since morphed into SGX, where Koos has a contact working in the Margin and Collateral Management space). Similarly, a lot of the credit risk involved in OTC (i.e. off-exchange) transactions has been reduced (or removed altogether) by the use of <b>ISDA</b> Credit Support Annex arrangements <a
href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_Support_Annex" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_Support_Annex</a> and latterly by regulatory initiatives such as <b>Dodd Frank</b> <a
href="http://www.ey.com/Publication/vwLUAssets/Key_questions_board_members_should_ask_about_Title_VII/$FILE/Americas_FAAS_Dodd_Frank_derivatives_reform.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.ey.com/Publication/vwLUAssets/Key_questions_board_members_should_ask_about_Title_VII/$FILE/Americas_FAAS_Dodd_Frank_derivatives_reform.pdf</a> and <b>EMIR</b> <a
href="https://www.esma.europa.eu/page/European-Market-Infrastructure-Regulation-EMIR" rel="nofollow">https://www.esma.europa.eu/page/European-Market-Infrastructure-Regulation-EMIR</a></p><p>The margining system has also evolved &#8211; back in the day Clearing Members typically made as much income from interest accruing on margin held from Customers as they did from brokerage commissions (under a system known as SPAN margining), but more recently VaR (Value at Risk) based margining has become more common, and in a lower interest rate environment the opportunities for windfall profits on margin balances have more or less evapourated.</p><p>A key qualification on the Maintenance Margin described in the article is the operation of Variation Margin, which is the requirement for counterparties with positions on Futures Exchanges to make additional payments (or deposit collateral) equivalent to the daily P&amp;L on their positions; the credit exposure is therefore effectively closed out by a daily Margin Call (i.e. the need to top up) and this again substantially reduces counterparty credit exposure. However, this has led to a very significant increase in Liquidity Risk (in the funding sense) and it was this in particular which posed significant challenges for both Lehmans and AIG.</p><p>Basically, whilst Initial Margin requirements are typically static (they do change, but not every day) Variation Margin is a function of market volatility, and if a counterparty is repeatedly called upon to &#8220;make good&#8221; unrealised lossed by posting additional margin or collateral, pretty soon it needs to start liquidating physical assets in order to meet the margin calls &#8211; either that, or close out the Futures position. This is a particular problem for investment Funds, which typically have tight constraints on both the amount of cash they are permitted to hold as a % of Assets, and  also upon the extent of credit available to them (if any) from their Prime Brokers or elsewhere. A big move in the markets can therefore lead to immediate pain being felt &#8211; not just in P&amp;L, but in short term liquidity and ultimately an overall performance hit on the Fund.</p><p>Finally, a word about Options; in the wholesale markets these are rarely traded with the intention of taking delivery of the Underlying at expiry (and on COMEX, the Underlying is not physical Gold, but a Futures contract). Options are leveraged polydimensional plays on a variety of market factors, many of which are not directly observable, but go by a variety of Greek names such as Gamma, Vega, Theta, Rho etc.The Strike Price of the Option is an important but not the only critical determinant of its value and &#8211; while there is still significant time left to Expiry, other factors such as Volatility may have an equally significant impact &#8211; especially where Options are traded as part of a composite strategy rather than in isolation. At all points up to close-to-Expiry, it is safest to consider Options as being fundamentally the same as Futures, albeit with curved price performance, rather than the straight line Profit/Loss payoff profile of a Futures Contract. To all intents and purposes Margin is calculated in pretty much the same way as Futures, and it is rare to find a totally naked Options position in the professional market</p><p>As an example, an At the Money Call option has a Delta of around 0.5, meaning that if the Futures Price goes up by 10 units, the value of the Option will increase by around 5 units. Typically, a Long position comprised of 2 Call contracts might be offset &#8211; or hedged &#8211; by going Short (i.e. selling) 1 Futures contract &#8211; netting out the Delta risk exposure and leaving the trader with a basket of other risks related to e.g. Volatility, Time Value, and the fact that Delta is not constant, but is curved and changes as the price of the Underlying moves relative to the Strike Price of the Option (Gamma). This may all sound confusing, but the basic message is that the notion that Options positions are held because a trader hopes or fears that a particular Strike price will be reached are too simplistic and mask more complex trading strategies which may not be immediately apparent to an outside observer.</p><p>Great stuff, Koos &#8211; keep it up!</p></div></div><ul
